</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t14h1s" class="update">Updated, 2:01 p.m. | </span></webonly>At a local art gallery in 2010, amid the loud chatter over wine and cheese, I heard a weird metronomic sound over toward one wall. I wandered over to find a hammer set to tap relentlessly on a sheet of glass, behind which were these words in red letters: &#8220;<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=edit?video_id=C1zgJjgggCM">BREAK GLASS IN CASE OF EMERGENCY</a>.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Tap&#8230;.Â Tap&#8230;.Â Tap&#8230;.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The chatter and laughter continued unabated.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Long-time readers here may recall what the artist, John Allen, said <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/04/23/in-case-of-emergency-tap-tap/">when I asked him about it</a>. He explained thatÂ he had originally set the piece up in his home to test whether it could both get under oneâs skin and also fade into the background.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The sculpture came to mind again this week when Anthony Leiserowitz, a Yale University researcher leading a longstanding effort to understand attitudes on global warming, distributed a note asking, &#8220;Is There a Climate &#8216;Spiral of Silence&#8217; in America?&#8221; He summarized a fresh analysis by a team atÂ <a href="//climatecommunication.yale.edu/">Yale</a>Â and <a href="//www.climatechangecommunication.org/">George Mason University</a>Â showing that while most Americans say they are somewhat or very interested in global warming, a bigger majority say they rarely or never talk about it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here are the data:Â <span id="more-58422"></span></p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/29/blogs/dotyaleclimatechat/dotyaleclimatechat-blog480.png" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/29/blogs/dotyaleclimatechat/dotyaleclimatechat-blog480.png" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/29/blogs/dotyaleclimatechat/dotyaleclimatechat-blog480.png" id="100000004680444" width="480" height="360" alt="Two thirds of Americans are moderately or very interested in global warming, &lt;a href=&quot;//climatecommunication.yale.edu/publications/climate-spiral-silence-america/&quot;&gt;according to a recent survey.&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="360"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Two thirds of Americans are moderately or very interested in global warming, <a href="//climatecommunication.yale.edu/publications/climate-spiral-silence-america/">according to a recent survey.</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Yale University and George Mason University</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/30/blogs/dotyaleclimatetalk/dotyaleclimatetalk-blog480.png" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/30/blogs/dotyaleclimatetalk/dotyaleclimatetalk-blog480.png" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/09/30/blogs/dotyaleclimatetalk/dotyaleclimatetalk-blog480.png" id="100000004681933" width="480" height="360" alt="&lt;a href=&quot;//climatecommunication.yale.edu/publications/climate-spiral-silence-america/&quot;&gt;A survey finds&lt;/a&gt; that most Americans rarely or never discuss global warming with family or friends."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="360"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"><a href="//climatecommunication.yale.edu/publications/climate-spiral-silence-america/">A survey finds</a> that most Americans rarely or never discuss global warming with family or friends.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Yale University and George Mason University</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Click <a href="//climatecommunication.yale.edu/publications/climate-spiral-silence-america/">here for the full analysis</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#8217;s notable that this reportÂ comes shortly after climate researchers concluded that carbon dioxide levels in the atmosphere have <a href="//www.climatecentral.org/news/world-passes-400-ppm-threshold-permanently-20738">passed the 400 parts per million threshold</a> in a way that&#8217;s essentially permanent &#8212; barring some extraordinary breakthrough in technologies capable of sopping up the gas for safekeeping &#8212; <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=gigaton+sequestration+co2&amp;oq=gigaton+sequestration+co2&amp;aqs=chrome..69i57.5991j0j4&amp;sourceid=chrome&amp;ie=UTF-8#q=gigaton+sequestration+co2&amp;tbm=nws">at the scale of billions of tons a year</a>. (I wrote <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/10/22/starting-later-this-year-400-and-up-is-likely-to-be-the-new-normal-for-co2-measurements/">about this inevitable moment last year</a>.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ralph Keeling, who leads the Scripps Institution of Oceanography effort tracking CO2 (following in <a href="//scrippsco2.ucsd.edu/charles_david_keeling_biography">the footsteps of his legendary father</a>), <a href="https://scripps.ucsd.edu/programs/keelingcurve/2016/09/23/note-on-reaching-the-annual-low-point/">wrote this a week ago</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Brief excursions towards lower values are still possible but it already seems safe to conclude that we wonât be seeing a monthly value below 400 ppm this year âÂ  or ever again for the indefinite future.</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another climate change milestone accrues, to go with the <a href="https://psmag.com/this-years-surge-in-global-warming-is-so-off-the-charts-a-comic-is-the-best-way-to-explain-it-3ced8e0e0247#.x6tv4ugw7">latest record highs in global temperature</a>, and a new analysis putting recent warming <a href="//news.nationalgeographic.com/2016/09/global-warming-study-13-degrees-is-wrong-climate-change/">in the context of 2 million years</a> of climate history.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As Randy Olson asserted years ago, could it be that the end of the world as we know it <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/10/27/global-warming-and-the-tyranny-of-boredom/">is simply &#8220;bo-ho-ho-ring&#8221;?</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In his note about the new analysis, Leiserowitz included an appeal for the public to weigh in:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our findings suggest that there is a climate change âspiral of silence,â in which even people who care about the issue, shy away from discussing it because they so infrequently hear other people talking about it â reinforcing the spiral.Â  Weâve synthesized these findings in our latest Climate Note &#8211; read it <a href="//yale.us2.list-manage1.com/track/click?u=78464048a89f4b58b97123336&amp;id=d697323523&amp;e=c6df58ce5b" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=//yale.us2.list-manage1.com/track/click?u%3D78464048a89f4b58b97123336%26id%3Dd697323523%26e%3Dc6df58ce5b&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1475335221002000&amp;usg=AFQjCNG25ZeN6T-eK1QCPJdTGlR7YOQncA">here</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What do you think? Do you think there a spiral of silence about climate change in America? Do you find yourself or others you know hesitant to talk about it? If so, why?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Please share your answers via Twitter to <a href="//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=78464048a89f4b58b97123336&amp;id=225bd9e8ac&amp;e=c6df58ce5b" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u%3D78464048a89f4b58b97123336%26id%3D225bd9e8ac%26e%3Dc6df58ce5b&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1475335221002000&amp;usg=AFQjCNG0tPXS9vaANCnWXMmvjaoK8fgTQA"><u>@YaleClimateComm</u></a> and <a href="//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=78464048a89f4b58b97123336&amp;id=ec579adc13&amp;e=c6df58ce5b" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u%3D78464048a89f4b58b97123336%26id%3Dec579adc13%26e%3Dc6df58ce5b&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1475335221002000&amp;usg=AFQjCNEdaEmri7CZp8N231qay_gT5NhfiQ"><u>@Mason4C</u></a>, using the hashtag <u>#climatesilence</u>, or on our Facebook pages: <a href="//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=78464048a89f4b58b97123336&amp;id=ba164c2b0a&amp;e=c6df58ce5b" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u%3D78464048a89f4b58b97123336%26id%3Dba164c2b0a%26e%3Dc6df58ce5b&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1475335221002000&amp;usg=AFQjCNE6h6oOqQ3r6wJT7I663VFRP8D9Jw"><u>Yale Program on Climate Change Communication</u></a> and <a href="//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u=78464048a89f4b58b97123336&amp;id=31db686496&amp;e=c6df58ce5b" target="_blank" data-saferedirecturl="https://www.google.com/url?hl=en&amp;q=//yale.us2.list-manage.com/track/click?u%3D78464048a89f4b58b97123336%26id%3D31db686496%26e%3Dc6df58ce5b&amp;source=gmail&amp;ust=1475335221002000&amp;usg=AFQjCNG5qF44DOIfMu_I44BHxH3j_VjqQw"><u>George Mason University Center for Climate Change Communication</u></a>. Letâs talk about it!</p></blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Share your thoughts here, as well, of course &#8212; with civility.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So what&#8217;s to be done about what I once called &#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/learning/students/pop/10REVK.html">global waffling</a>&#8220;?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Ask George Marshall, the longtime climate campaigner, student of behavioral and social science and author of the most sobering and essential book on the issue: &#8220;<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Dont-Even-Think-About-Climate/dp/1501277014">Don&#8217;t Even Think About It: Why Our Brains Are Wired to Ignore Climate</a>.&#8221;</p>
<div class="w480">
<div class="w480 youtube-video-container">
<div class="youtube-video" data-youtube-id="Ayo7GsDuS94" data-start="">
<div class="thumb"><img src="https://img.youtube.com/vi/Ayo7GsDuS94/0.jpg" />
<div class="playButton">
<div class="arrow"></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/sep/23/why-our-brains-wired-ignore-climate-change-united-nations">He says the first step is to recognize</a>, even embrace, the essence of how humans work, including the faults. Then new conversations and collaborations can build.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This is in synch with my notion of &#8220;<a href="https://www.edge.org/response-detail/11738">Anthropophilia</a>.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#8217;s this kind of work that has led me to focus more on fostering traits in society that can boost capacities to innovate, empathize, to deviseÂ resilient responses to risks and more &#8212; <a href="//dotearth.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/12/we-are-perfect-with-an-asterisk/">to bend, stretch, reach, teach&#8230;.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Postscript, 2:05 p.m.</strong> | It never hurts to try fresh pathways to engagement, including music (as <a href="//j.mp/libcarb">I&#8217;ve tried myself</a>). That&#8217;s why it&#8217;s worth drawing attention to a techno composition built around the Keeling carbon dioxide data <a href="//www.washington.edu/news/2016/09/30/co2-record-at-mauna-loa-the-music-video-the-sounds-of-climate-change/">by two climate scientists at the University of Washington</a>:</p>
